Yet, in spite of these defects, the play is excellent reading, and we must remember that such blemishes in artistic execution would be hardly noticeable in a piece which must have far more resembled an opera bouffe than a modern comedy. The plays of Plautus were⁴ acted without any division into acts and scenes,† or any pause, except when the plot requ1red that an actor should leave the stage at the end of one scene and appear again at the beginning of the next. In these cases a tibicen entertained the spectators while the stage was empty. This is ex- pressly referred to in the pseudulus at the end of the first Act, and no doubt under these circumstances the tibicen was always resorted to: but except in such cases there was no pause in the acting.
